{"cursor":"10880","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\nThe 'Larsen Ice Shelf' is a long, fringing ice shelf in the northwest part of\nthe Weddell Sea, extending along the east coast of Antarctic Peninsula from Cape\nLonging to the area just southward of Hearst Island. Named for Captain Carl\nAnton Larsen, the master of the Norwegian whaling vessel [[Jason (ship)|Jason]],\nwho sailed along the ice front as far as 68Â°10' South during December\n1893.\n\nIn finer detail, the Larsen Ice Shelf is a series of three shelves that occupy\n(or occupied) distinct embayments along the coast. From north to south, the\nthree segments are called Larsen A (the smallest), Larsen B, and Larsen C (the\nlargest) by researchers who work in the area. The Larsen A ice shelf\ndisintegrated in January 1995. [http://www.scientificamerican.com/article.cfm?id=scientists-trek-\ncollapsing-glaciers-antarctica-meltdown Scientists Trek to Collapsing Glaciers\nto Assess Antarcticaâs Meltdown and Sea-Level Rise] July 16, 2012 Scientific\nAmerican The Larsen B ice shelf disintegrated in February 2002. The Larsen\nC ice shelf appeared to be stable in 2008, though scientists predict that, if\nlocalized warming continues at its current rate, the shelf could disintegrate at\nsome point within the foreseeable\nfuture. [http://cires.colorado.edu/science/pro/irp/2008/scambos/ Larsen C\nthinning]\n\nThe Larsen disintegration events were unusual by past standards. Typically, ice\nshelves lose mass by iceberg calving and by melting at their upper and lower\nsurfaces. The disintegration events are linked to the ongoing climate warming in\nthe Antarctic Peninsula, about 0.5 Â°C per decade since the late 1940s,\nwhich is a consequence of localized warming of the Antarctic peninsula. Connor, Steve (2005) \"Ice shelf collapse was biggest for\n10,000 years since Ice Age\" The Independent, London (Aug 4),\n[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_20050804/ai_n14872277 online] This localized warming is caused by anthropogenic global\nwarming, according to some scientists through strengthening of the Antarctic\nannular winds. Marshall et al.,\n[http://www.atmos.colostate.edu/ao/other_papers/Marshall_etal_JClimate2006.pdf\n\"The Impact of a Changing Southern Hemisphere Annular Mode on Antarctic\nPeninsula Summer Temperatures\"], Journal of Climate, 'vol. 19', pp. 5388â5404,\nOctober 2006.\n\n File:Larsen iceshelves.png|Larsen A and Larsen B\niceshelves marked in red. File:Glacier-ice shelf interactions.svg|Glacier-ice\nshelf interactions. File:Antarctic Peninsula, the Larsen Ice Shelf, and the sea\nice covered waters around the region.jpg|Clear view of the Antarctic Peninsula,\nthe Larsen Ice Shelf, and the sea ice covered waters around the region.\n\n","linknr":238,"url":"Larsen_Ice_Shelf","recorded":1374767484,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Larsen_Ice_Shelf&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Larsen_Ice_Shelf&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/File:Larsen_B_collapse.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/12/Larsen_B_collapse.jpg/275px-Larsen_B_collapse.jpg","/wiki/File:Larsen_B_collapse.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.22wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-cli